{{Infobox religious building | name = {{nihongo|'''Yusuhara Hachiman-gū'''|柞原八幡宮||}} | image = Higurashimon.JPG | caption = The south gate of Yusuhara Shrine is called ''Higurashimon'', meaning a "gate from sunrise till sunset" | map_type = Japan | map_alt = | coordinates = {{coord|33|14|18.1|N|131|33|3.6|E|region:JP-44_type:landmark|display=title,inline}} | map_relief = | map_size = | map_caption = | religious_affiliation = [[Shinto]] | type = | deity = | founded_by = | established = | date_destroyed = | location = | website = | architecture_style = | festival = | leadership = }} {{nihongo|'''Yusuhara Hachiman-gū'''|柞原八幡宮||}}, also known as '''Yasuhara Shrine''', is a Japanese [[Shinto shrine]] in [[Oita, Oita]] on the island of [[Kyushu]].<ref name="kotodamayama">Kotodamaya.com, [http://www.kotodamaya.com/yasuhara-hachiman/ "Yasuhara Hachimangu"]; retrieved 2012-10-25.</ref>
==History== Yusuhara is believed to have been built in the early 9th century. It was established as a branch shrine temple (''miyadera'') of ''[[Usa jingū]].''<ref>Oita City Tourist Association, [http://www.oishiimati-oita.jp/english/hannichi.html "Yusuhara Hachiman Shrine"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080611194605/http://www.oishiimati-oita.jp/english/hannichi.html |date=June 11, 2008 }}; Haruko Nawata, [https://books.google.com/books?id=saX0gHc91fkC&pg=PA124&lpg=PA124&dq=yusuhara+hachimangu&source=bl&ots=GS5ILq1ipI&sig=f6dYQXTFh_0sm_nV6zMlnz-6W2E&hl=en&sa=X&ei=8paKUKasMub50gGdkoDYDA&ved=0CDkQ6AEwBjgK#v=onepage&q=yusuhara%20hachimangu&f=false ''Women Religious Leaders in Japan's Christian Century, 1549-1650,'' p. 124n50]; retrieved 2012-10-25.</ref>
Yusuhara was the chief Shinto shrine (''[[ichinomiya]]'') of the old [[Bungo Province]]. It serves today as one of the ''ichinomiya'' of [[Niigata Prefecture]]. <ref>[http://eos.kokugakuin.ac.jp/modules/xwords/images/uploads/EOS070712Ab.pdf "Nationwide List of ''Ichinomiya''," p. 3]; retrieved 2012-10-25.</ref> The enshrined ''[[kami]]'' are: * {{nihongo|Chuai tenno|仲哀天皇||}}<ref name="kotodamayama"/> * {{nihongo|Emperor Oojin|応神天皇||}}<ref name="kotodamayama"/> * {{nihongo|Empress Jingu|神功皇后||}}<ref name="kotodamayama"/>
In 1916, the shrine was listed among the 3rd class of nationally significant shrines or {{nihongo|''Kokuhei Shōsha''|国幣小社}} .<ref>Holton, Daniel Clarence. (1922). [https://books.google.com/books?id=6y8VAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA270&lpg=PA270&dq= ''The political philosophy of modern Shintō: a study of the state religion of Japan,'' p. 270].</ref>
